Mount Airy’s 2025 Turkey Day Fun Run: Is Your Family Protected on the Course?

Before you lace up for the Surry County tradition, let's talk safety and coverage.

By Bill Layne Principal Agent • 20+ Years Experience
Nov 19, 2025
Mount Airy, NC

It’s almost time to earn that pumpkin pie! The Mount Airy Turkey Day Fun Run is a beloved tradition here in the foothills. Whether you are a serious runner aiming for a personal best or a family looking to walk off some calories before the big meal, it's a fantastic way to start the holiday.

However, amidst the excitement of gathering with neighbors and enjoying the crisp North Carolina air, very few participants stop to think about the "what ifs." As your local insurance experts in Elkin and Mount Airy, we want to ensure your holiday is memorable for the right reasons—not because of an unexpected accident.

Race Day Snapshot

Mark your calendars for this year's event!

  • Date: Thursday, November 27, 2025 (Thanksgiving Day)
  • Location: Mount Airy, NC
  • Check the Town of Mount Airy website for registration details

1. The "Oops" Moment: Personal Liability Insurance

Picture this: You’re at the starting line, packed in with hundreds of other excited runners. The horn blows, everyone surges forward, and in the chaos, you accidentally trip a fellow runner. If they suffer a serious injury and decide to hold you responsible for their medical bills, are you covered?

This is where the Personal Liability portion of your homeowners or renters insurance policy steps in. It generally provides coverage for bodily injury or property damage you unintentionally cause to others—even if it happens away from your home, like on a race course near Riverside Park.

Stay safe and stretch before hitting the pavement.

2. Protecting Your Gear: Off-Premises Theft

While Mount Airy is known for its friendly, Mayberry-like atmosphere, leaving valuables visible in your car is never a good idea. If you leave your phone, wallet, or expensive running watch in your vehicle while you run, and a break-in occurs, your auto insurance typically won't cover the stolen items.

Instead, this falls under your homeowners or renters policy as "off-premises" personal property coverage. Be aware that your deductible will apply. If you're running with expensive tech, you might want to consider a "scheduled personal property" endorsement for broader coverage with no deductible.

3. Health Insurance vs. Medical Payments

If you trip on a root or a pothole and injure yourself, your primary health insurance is your first line of defense. However, check if you have Medical Payments to Others on your home policy. While "Med Pay" on a home policy usually covers guests injured on your property, understanding your health deductibles before an active event is crucial.

Additionally, for those traveling from outside Surry County—perhaps visiting family in Raleigh or Charlotte—ensure your health plan covers urgent care visits in our area to avoid surprise "out-of-network" costs.

Review Your Coverage Before the Race

Don't let an accident ruin your holiday weekend. Let us review your homeowners and auto policies to ensure you have the right liability limits for your active lifestyle.

Frequently Asked Questions

Does my homeowners insurance cover me if I accidentally injure someone during a race?

Generally, yes. The personal liability portion of your homeowners or renters policy typically follows you anywhere in the world, acting as a financial shield if you are found liable for injuring someone else accidentally.

What if my phone is stolen from my car while I'm running?

Items stolen from your vehicle are usually NOT covered by auto insurance. Instead, they are covered by your homeowners or renters insurance under "off-premises" personal property coverage, subject to your deductible.

Do I need special event insurance to participate?

No, participants generally do not need to buy a specific "event policy." Standard personal liability and health insurance are usually sufficient. However, race organizers will likely ask you to sign a waiver releasing them from liability.
